<h3 id=3D"Syllabus-SpecialCourseProvisions:"><strong>Special Course Provisi=
ons:</strong></h3>
<p><em>Here is some default policy statement to test the fetching ability o=
f v2 API endpoints being experimented with.</em></p>
<p></p>
<h2 local-id=3D"b7107e55922c" id=3D"Syllabus-CourseRequirementsandGradingPo=
licies:">
<style>[data-colorid=3Duggjmbf1am]{color:#bf2600} html[data-color-mode=3Dda=
rk] [data-colorid=3Duggjmbf1am]{color:#ff6640}</style>Course Requirements a=
nd Grading Policies:</h2>
<p local-id=3D"f3831053bce4"><strong><span data-colorid=3D"uggjmbf1am">JCPH=
 Canvas Onboarding Training (2025 updates):</span></strong></p>
<p local-id=3D"2eb53ac54a0f">Complete the module on AI usage if you have no=
t already done so: =E2=80=98<a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://jeff=
erson.instructure.com/courses/7062/modules/449017" rel=3D"nofollow">What Ab=
out AI in the Classroom?</a>=E2=80=99</p>
<p local-id=3D"199d92121366"><strong>Attendance and Participation:</strong>=
</p>
<p local-id=3D"911478bde639">A significant part of your grade for this cour=
se will be based on attendance and participation. In our online learning en=
vironment, the attendance and participation take the form of your contribut=
ions to the discussions on the class Discussion Board and your contribution=
s to the learning community.</p>
<p local-id=3D"dc99d181b1a1">You will earn the most participation points by=
 making regular, high-quality postings to the discussion forums, providing =
your feedback on the weekly '5-min. feedback' surveys, and submitting the f=
inal course evaluation. Responses to both weekly feedback and the final cou=
rse evaluation are always kept confidential.</p>
<p local-id=3D"e38365faa6f6"><strong>Minimum participation requirements:</s=
trong> Each week or module, all participants must post to <em>each</em> dis=
cussion topic a minimum of <em>three</em> times. These postings must be mad=
e on at least two different days during the week/module. (You should not ma=
ke all three postings on the same day.)</p>
<p local-id=3D"b0cbcc89b14d"><strong>First posting before midnight, Wednesd=
ay:</strong> make your first post to the current week=E2=80=99s/module's di=
scussion topics early---before midnight Wednesday. This posting is your ori=
ginal, individual response to each of the discussion questions presented fo=
r the week/module.</p>
<p local-id=3D"7a18d19b1aa1"><strong>Second posting before noon, Saturday:<=
/strong> make your second set of posts toward the end of the week/module or=
 early on the weekend (before Saturday, noon). Respond to at least two of y=
our classmates' postings in each of the week's/module's discussion forums.<=
/p>
<p local-id=3D"7fe319f82ee2"><em>See the course points allocation table loc=
ated on the last page/screen of the syllabus for the number of discussion f=
orums in your course and their point value.</em></p>
<p local-id=3D"3f2c4ee774b8"><strong>Policy Regarding Late Work:</strong></=
p>
<p local-id=3D"0892658439d9">a. Our course is structured around weekly less=
ons or modules. A week/module is considered to <strong>begin on a Monday an=
d end the following Sunday.</strong> Depending on your class schedule, some=
 modules may span more than one week.</p>
<p local-id=3D"2ba03a50a381">i. All postings to discussions should be <em>c=
ompleted by midnight Sunday</em> for the week/module that is ending. No poi=
nts will be given for discussion postings not made by the close of the week=
/module (because your postings are meant to be read by others, and their va=
lue diminishes significantly once the class has moved on to the new week/mo=
dule).</p>
<p local-id=3D"57c006fe1c93">ii. All assignments other than discussions <st=
rong>are due by Sunday at midnight&nbsp;</strong>of the current week/module=
 unless otherwise specified in an assignment's instructions. Always review =
each assignment's instructions for complete information about its submissio=
n requirements.</p>
<p local-id=3D"b8635d6a9036">The least flexible types of assignments, when =
it comes to completion dates, are:</p>
<ol start=3D"1" local-id=3D"46a522c355af">
<li local-id=3D"3b79e38a43a9">
<p local-id=3D"921198e19535">Discussions: you need to keep pace with the cl=
ass or else the class discussion fragments.</p></li>
</ol>
<ol start=3D"1" local-id=3D"1ab7500ce688">
<li local-id=3D"f1594720e757">
<p local-id=3D"cde21a01ab1c">Pair or group work: you must not negatively im=
pact the progress of your classmates.</p></li>
</ol>
<p local-id=3D"18ec6f5cb765"><strong>Writing Standards (APA Guidelines):</s=
trong></p>
<p local-id=3D"e6b11fa9ec97">Papers and other documents submitted as course=
 work are to conform to APA style guidelines. These guidelines can be revie=
wed in the JCPH Canvas Onboarding training, where a model paper in general =
APA style can also be found: <a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://jef=
ferson.instructure.com/courses/7062/pages/readings-and-resources?module_ite=
m_id=3D1315666" rel=3D"nofollow">APA Guidelines</a>. APA conventions for th=
e use of title pages, page formatting, in-text citations, the attribution o=
f quotations, Reference lists, and all other elements of your documents mus=
t be adhered to in order to receive full credit on written assignments. Thi=
s includes APA stylistics covering point of view, word choice, clarity and =
conciseness. Electronic sources and other non-print materials must be refer=
enced per APA guidelines developed for that purpose.</p>
<p local-id=3D"0825423d8562">The only exceptions to this College policy are=
:</p>
<ul local-id=3D"f18e874a83c6">
<li local-id=3D"6274c89306ab">
<p local-id=3D"3acf70a9c599">Instructors may substitute another style stand=
ard, such as that of the American Medical Association, for the APA standard=
 so long as the alternative standard is equally comprehensive and equally a=
 part of the evaluation of written work.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"3cc6330c5e98">
<p local-id=3D"3db3ae8f63de">Documents of less than 2000 words (excluding R=
eference list and any appendices) need not carry an Abstract or list of key=
words.</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"db952d6947c0"><strong>Use of AI Tools for Coursework:</stron=
g></p>
<p local-id=3D"303b5c9415c3">The use of generative AI tools for coursework,=
 including conducting analyses or creating content, is permitted only if ex=
plicitly approved by the instructor.</p>
<p local-id=3D"e14eac664844">In alignment with the College's commitment to =
academic integrity, students are expected to submit coursework that is genu=
inely their own. Each student is accountable for the academic integrity of =
their submitted work and for upholding privacy, confidentiality, and intell=
ectual property rights.</p>
<p local-id=3D"e45b4714c270">When granted permission by the instructor to u=
se AI tools, students must adhere strictly to the instructor=E2=80=99s guid=
elines. This includes citing all AI-derived sources and producing all evide=
nce of authenticity that may be called for by an assignment=E2=80=99s instr=
uctions. Such evidence may include drafts of work, prompts, scripts, screen=
shots, primary data, or other documentation.</p>
<p local-id=3D"9f9dcf36577e">The College=E2=80=99s policy is based upon Jef=
ferson University=E2=80=99s standards for 'Restricted Use' of generative AI=
. For further details, see the policy statement: <a class=3D"external-link"=
 href=3D"https://www.jefferson.edu/life-at-jefferson/handbooks/policies/gra=
duate-policies/artificial-intelligence.html" rel=3D"nofollow">Graduate Poli=
cies: Artificial Intelligence</a>.</p>
<p local-id=3D"d0c4ac18b7f1"><strong>TJU Academic Integrity Policy:</strong=
></p>
<p local-id=3D"a6106cae5ff3">Academic Integrity is the foundation of all Je=
fferson teaching, learning, and professional endeavors and is vital to adva=
ncing a culture of fairness, trust and respect. All members of the Universi=
ty community must maintain respect for the intellectual efforts of others a=
nd be honest in their own work, words, and ideas.</p>
<p local-id=3D"aa59e070607b">Policy:&nbsp; <a class=3D"external-link" href=
=3D"https://www.jefferson.edu/life-at-jefferson/handbooks/policies/graduate=
-policies/academic-integrity.html" rel=3D"nofollow"><strong>Graduate Progra=
ms</strong></a><br>
Policy:<strong> </strong><a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://www.jef=
ferson.edu/life-at-jefferson/handbooks/policies/undergraduate-policies/acad=
emic-integrity.html" rel=3D"nofollow"><strong>Undergraduate Programs</stron=
g></a></p>
<p local-id=3D"0f1934ee9c3f"><strong>Use of 'Turnitin' (automated originali=
ty reporting tool):</strong></p>
<p local-id=3D"485189000ce4">Turnitin is used to prevent plagiarism and to =
help students identify how to properly attribute sources. It does so by com=
paring submitted assignments against a database of academic papers and inte=
rnet information to identify areas of overlap between the submitted assignm=
ent and existing works, producing a "similarity report." The similarity sco=
re is a percentage of an assignment=E2=80=99s content that matches the sear=
ched databases. Students and faculty should analyze the results of the repo=
rt to determine if plagiarism has occurred.</p>
<p local-id=3D"09f8ca03db15"><strong>GPA and Related Requirements:&nbsp;</s=
trong> Please refer to the JCPH Student Handbook located under 'Handbooks a=
nd Forms' on the Student Resources page: <a class=3D"external-link" href=3D=
"https://www.jefferson.edu/academics/colleges-schools-institutes/population=
-health/student-resources/handbooks-forms.html" rel=3D"nofollow"><strong>Ha=
ndbooks &amp; Forms</strong></a></p>
<p local-id=3D"31dedecd6ccb"><strong>Evaluation and Grading:</strong></p>
<p local-id=3D"7963b6b4f417">Students can earn up to 250 points in this cou=
rse by the end of the term.&nbsp; All graded activities in this course earn=
 points as they are completed and graded. At the end of the term, each stud=
ent's point total will be converted to a percentage based on the 250 point =
scale to determine the final course grade.</p>
<p local-id=3D"9fbec81bfadd">Students who have earned all 250 points in a c=
ourse will have a cumulative score of 100%. Students who have earned 225 po=
ints will have a 90% score, and so on. These percentages will then be conve=
rted to letter grades in keeping the College's standard grading scale.&nbsp=
;</p>
